{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17418340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17418340"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T10:32:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T10:32:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261502"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261502"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13877"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523103"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:52:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:52:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13877"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261502"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T10:32:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:35:00+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":2,"questionsAnswered":1,"marksTotal":1,"marksAttainable":1,"marksAttempted":1,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T10:32:18+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"13877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13877"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.09,0.32,0.24,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6494"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61597"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6494"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13877"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47050"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2145"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2360"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12896"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13860"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17342"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17347"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30643"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61597"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to a rural General Practice clinic with intense pain and swelling of his right hand following a workplace accident. He reports accidentally injecting his hand with a Sheep Johne\u0027s Disease vaccine (Gudair) while working on his farm. He immediately cleansed the area after the incident. The patient brings the vaccine packaging, which indicates it is a paraffin oil-based vaccine and that medical attention should be sought immediately if accidently injected. His tetanus vaccination is up to date. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears distressed with a pulse rate of 90/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His right hand is swollen, erythematous, and tender to touch.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discharge home with oral antibiotics and analgesia","Check baseline HIV, hepatitis B and hepatitis C status","Immediate referral to plastic surgery for surgical debridement","Immediately incise the skin to reduce the risk of compartment syndrome","Admit to the local hospital for 48 hours of intravenous antibiotics"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmediate referral to plastic surgery for surgical debridement\u003C/strong\u003E. Accidental injection of oil-based vaccines, such as the Sheep Johne\u0027s Disease vaccine (Gudair), can cause severe tissue damage and necrosis due to the oil base. Surgical debridement is crucial as it directly addresses the necrotic tissue, removing the damaged and potentially infected tissue to prevent further spread and preserve hand function. This situation is considered a surgical emergency, and prompt debridement is crucial to prevent further tissue damage and potential loss of function. Tetanus status should be checked and a booster administered if required. Prophylactic antibiotics are also often given to prevent secondary infection from potentially contaminated needles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarging home with oral antibiotics and analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate for this type of injury. While antibiotics may help prevent secondary infection, they do not address the primary issue of mechanical tissue damage caused by the oil-based vaccine. The patient requires immediate surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChecking baseline HIV, hepatitis B and hepatitis C status\u003C/strong\u003E is not relevant in this acute situation. While it might be part of a routine occupational health follow-up, it does not address the urgent need for managing the hand injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediately incising the skin\u003C/strong\u003E to reduce the risk of compartment syndrome is not recommended. This procedure should only be performed by a specialist in a controlled setting, as improper technique could cause further damage or introduce infection. Compartment syndrome would only be considered with very large volume injections, above that typically administered in a single vaccination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmitting to the local hospital for 48 hours of intravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient. While antibiotics may be part of the treatment plan, they do not address the urgent need for surgical debridement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, accidental injection of oil-based vaccines requires urgent surgical intervention to prevent severe tissue damage and potential loss of function. The patient should be immediately referred to a plastic surgeon or hand specialist for proper assessment and surgical debridement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlease note that agricultural workers and farmers can and should report any adverse event to the Australian Pesticides and Veterinary Medicine Authority (APVMA) and be encouraged to do so. Similarly, health and medical professionals should also report any adverse patient experience.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Immediate referral for surgical debridement is crucial in managing accidental injection of oil-based vaccines to prevent severe tissue damage and necrosis.","Oil-based vaccine injections can cause significant tissue damage and should be treated as a surgical emergency.","Antibiotics are often administered to prevent infection however alone are insufficient in managing oil-based vaccine injections"],"references":["Burke F, Robertson C, Ackerman N, Reilly W. Needlestick and inoculation injuries in veterinary and animal workers. In Practice. 2017 Mar;39(3):138\u201341. Available at: https://farmerhealth.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/20190717-Farmer-Needlestick-Injuries-Risk-and-Recommended-Treatment.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47050"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13877"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47050"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T21:35:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T21:36:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6494"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61597"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","syn